Albert Camus was a French writer and philosopher born in Algeria in 1913. He is best known for novels like The Stranger and The Plague which explored themes of absurdism and existentialism. Camus received the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1957 for his body of work. He was also politically engaged as a champion of individual rights who opposed French colonization of Algeria. Camus died in a car accident in 1960 at the young age of 46.
